laxation","Isovolumetric contraction","Ventricular filling","Ventricular ejection","Atrial contraction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the cardiac cycle, left ventricular pressure varies significantly. The highest left ventricular pressure occurs during the \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular ejection\u003C/strong\u003E phase, when the left ventricle contracts forcefully to expel blood into the aorta against systemic arterial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other phases of the cardiac cycle are characterised by lower left ventricular pressures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsovolumetric relaxation\u003C/strong\u003E: Pressure rapidly decreases as the ventricle relaxes, but all valves are closed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsovolumetric contraction\u003C/strong\u003E: Pressure increases, but it\u0027s not yet high enough to open the aortic valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular filling\u003C/strong\u003E: Pressure is low to allow blood to flow from the atrium into the ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial contraction\u003C/strong\u003E: There\u0027s a slight increase in ventricular pressure, but it remains lower than during ejection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Left ventricular pressure is highest during the ventricular ejection phase of the cardiac cycle.","The cardiac cycle consists of five main phases: isovolumetric contraction, ventricular ejection, isovolumetric relaxation, ventricular filling, and atrial contraction."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Silverthorn D